04924nam a22006855i 9780813567235DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20162015nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2014049331  a97808135672357 a10.36019/97808135672352doi  a(DE-B1597)526432  a(OCoLC)1007092180  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aPN1995.9.P7bP745 2016 4aPN1995.9.P7P745 2015 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a791.43023300aProducing /ced. by Jon Lewis. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2016] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b26 photos, 2 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBehind the Silver Screen Series00tFrontmatter -- tBehind the Silver Screen -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Silent Screen, 1895–1927 -- t2. Classical Hollywood, 1928–1946 -- t3. Postwar Hollywood, 1947–1967 -- t4. The Auteur Renaissance, 1968–1980 -- t5. The New Hollywood, 1981–1999 -- t6. The Modern Entertainment Marketplace, 2000–Present -- tAcademy Awards for Producing -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOf all the job titles listed in the opening and closing screen credits, producer is certainly the most amorphous. There are businessmen (and women)-producers, writer-director- and movie-star-producers; producers who work for the studio; executive producers whose reputation and industry clout alone gets a project financed (though their day-to-day participation in the project may be negligible). The job title, regardless of the actual work involved, warrants a great deal of prestige in the film business; it is the credited producers, after all, who collect the Oscar for Best Picture. But what producers do and what they don’t or won’t do varies from project to project. Producing is the first book to provide a comprehensive overview of the roles that producers have played in Hollywood, from the dawn of the twentieth century to the present day. It introduces readers to the colorful figures who helped to define and reimagine the producer’s role, including inventors like Thomas Edison, moguls like Darryl F. Zanuck, entrepreneurs like Walt Disney, and mavericks like Roger Corman. Readers also get an inside look at the less glamorous jobs producers have often performed: shepherding projects through many years of development, securing financial backers, and supervising movie shoots. The latest book in the acclaimed Behind the Silver Screen series, Producing includes essays written by seven film scholars, each an expert in a different period of cinema history. Together, they give readers a full picture of how the art and business of producing films has changed over time—and how the producer’s myriad job duties continue to evolve in the digital era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMotion picture industry. 0aMotion picturesxProduction and direction. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Mark Lynn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, Mark Lynn.1 aGiovacchini, Saverio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiovacchini, Saverio.1 aGomery, Douglas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGomery, Douglas.1 aGrantham, Bill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrantham, Bill.1 aLewis, Jon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Jon, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLewis, Jon.1 aMiller, Toby, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Toby.1 aRapf, Joanna E.1 aRapf, Joanna E., econtributor.4ctb4htt